# Kung Fu Chess — Cursor Agent Instructions

**Read this file first.** It is the canonical entry point for Cursor Agent in this repo.

## Cursor workflow

1. Identify which architectural layer the task belongs to (see Architecture below)
2. Apply layer-specific rules from `.cursor/rules/` when editing matching paths
3. Keep diffs minimal — change only what the task requires
4. After adding `.cpp` files, update `build.bat` and `CMakeLists.txt`
5. Verify with `.\build.bat` or `.\build.bat test` when logic changes; use `.\build.bat graphics-test` for OpenCV graphics unit tests
6. If the change affects layout, architecture, layers, build, input protocol, or conventions — update the instruction files to match:
   - `.cursor/rules/agents.mdc` (primary)
   - `AGENTS.md` (keep in sync with agents.mdc)
   - Relevant `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` (e.g. `architecture.mdc`, `model-rules.mdc`)
7. Do not commit unless the user explicitly asks

### Layer rule files (apply when editing matching files)

| Rule file | Globs |
|-----------|-------|
| `cpp-files.mdc` | `src/**`, `include/**` |
| `cpp-quality.mdc` | `src/**/*.cpp`, `src/**/*.h`, `include/**/*.h` |
| `model-rules.mdc` | `model/`, `rules/` |
| `engine-realtime.mdc` | `engine/`, `realtime/` |
| `io-input-view.mdc` | `io/`, `input/`, `view/`, `texttests/`, `main.cpp`, `App` |

## Stack

- C++17, STL only for the engine, console app, and tests — no third-party deps there
- Headers in `include/`, sources in `src/`
- Build: `.\build.bat` builds and runs the app (`src\main.cpp` composition root); `.\build.bat test` builds and runs the engine test suite (includes STL graphics tests for board CSV / config / asset paths); `.\build.bat graphics-test` builds and runs OpenCV graphics unit tests; `.\build.bat server` builds the WebSocket server (requires `third_party/` deps — see README)
- **Graphics only:** use the Qama Tech `Img` wrapper (`include/view/Img.h`, `src/view/Img.cpp`) from the course repo; OpenCV is allowed **only** inside that `Img` class (bundled `OpenCV_451` for `build.bat graphics` / `graphics-test`). No other graphics or rendering libraries (SDL, SFML, GLFW, etc.). Never `#include <opencv2/...>` outside `Img.h` / `Img.cpp` — all other graphics code (`graphics/`, `Renderer`, `GraphicsApplication`, `graphics_main`) goes through the `Img` API. `build.bat graphics` builds `src/graphics_main.cpp` (composition root: default online WebSocket + shell AUTH, or `--offline`) + `GraphicsApplication` (frame loop via injected `IFrameStateSource` / `IMatchmaker`, `PieceVisual` animations).

## Language

- **All comments must be in English and need to be short** — never Hebrew or mixed-language comments
- Identifiers, error strings, and reason codes: English only

## Layout

```
include/
├── model/       Board, Piece, Position, GameState
├── rules/       IPieceRules strategies (one *Rules.{h,cpp} per piece), RuleEngine
├── realtime/    Motion, MotionView, Rest, RestView, RealTimeArbiter
├── engine/      GameEngine
├── io/          BoardParser, BoardPrinter (IBoardPrinter)
├── input/       Controller, BoardMapper
├── graphics/    Animation, AnimationLoader, AnimationCache (AnimationSpec), BoardLayout, PieceVisual, IFrameStateSource, LocalEngineStateSource
├── client/      WebSocketClient, InboundMessageQueue, SessionBootstrap, RemoteStateSource, IMatchmaker (graphics online path)
├── view/        Img (OpenCV wrapper), Renderer
├── texttests/   ScriptParser (IScriptSource), ScriptRunner, ScriptCommand
├── bus/         EventBus (Observer pub/sub), GameEvent, MoveLog/Sound/MoveHistory/Rating subscribers
├── auth/        AuthController → UserService → UserRepository; PasswordHasher (bcrypt), Elo
├── protocol/    Algebraic, CommandParser, StateSerializer, StateDeserializer
├── server/      GameSession, MatchRoom, MatchQueue, ConnectionRegistry, MatchCoordinator, RoomManager, WebSocketServer
├── App.h        Composition root (console)
└── GraphicsApplication.h  Interactive graphics frame loop (injected IFrameStateSource + IMatchmaker)
```

> Legacy `Board.h`/`Board.cpp`, `Game.h`/`Game.cpp`, `MoveRules.h`/`MoveRules.cpp` are removed.
> `src/main.cpp` is the composition root: it constructs the concrete `ScriptParser` (an `IScriptSource`)
> and `BoardPrinter` (an `IBoardPrinter`), injects them into `ScriptRunner` by const reference, then calls
> `ScriptRunner::run(std::cin, std::cout)`, which parses the `Board:`/`Commands:` protocol and replays it
> against `GameEngine` + `Controller`.
> `src/server_main.cpp` hosts the WebSocket server: protocol → `ConnectionRegistry` +
> `MatchCoordinator`/`MatchQueue` → `RoomManager`/`MatchRoom`/`GameSession` →
> existing `GameEngine`, publishing events on the Observer `EventBus`. Clients `AUTH username password`,
> then `PLAY` for ELO±100 matchmaking (60s → `match_not_found`); a found match seats W/B on a new
> `MatchRoom` (multiple concurrent matches). `Viewer` stub for non-play clients; full Rooms/spectator
> broadcast still TODO. Users/ratings in SQLite via `auth/` (`AuthController` → `UserService` →
> `UserRepository`, bcrypt hashes). Per-match `RatingSubscriber` updates ELO on `GameEnded` through `UserService`.
> `SoundSubscriber` plays WAV cues from `assets/sounds/` (`select`, `deselect`, `move`, `jump`, `capture`,
> `promote`, `game_end`, `game_start`). Graphics shows a centered **GAME OVER** banner when the game ends,
> and White/Black side panels list moves (piece, from-to, game-clock time) and capture
> `SCORE` (material: P1 N/B3 R5 Q9) via `MoveHistorySubscriber`.
> `GameEvent::timeMs` is stamped from `GameEngine::elapsedMs()` in the graphics app only.

## Architecture

Dependencies point inward only:

```
main/App → input/view/io → engine → rules/realtime → model
server_main → server/protocol/bus/auth → engine → rules/realtime → model
```

| Layer | Key types | Responsibility |
|-------|-----------|----------------|
| Model | `Board`, `Piece`, `Position`, `GameState` | Grid data, bounds — no I/O or rules |
| Rules | `IPieceRules`, `RuleEngine` | Move legality via Strategy pattern |
| Realtime | `Motion`, `RealTimeArbiter` | Timed movement, capture on arrival |
| Engine | `GameEngine` | Orchestrates model + rules + realtime |
| I/O | `BoardParser`, `BoardPrinter` | Parse/serialize board text |
| Input | `Controller`, `BoardMapper` | Map clicks/pixels to engine calls |
| Bus | `EventBus`, `GameEvent`, subscribers | Observer pub/sub for score/log/sound/UI/rating (`MoveMade`, `JumpMade`, `PieceCaptured`, `PiecePromoted`, `PieceSelected`, `SelectionCleared`, `GameEnded`, `ScoreUpdated`, …); graphics uses `MoveHistorySubscriber` for side-panel lines + SCORE; server uses `RatingSubscriber` for ELO; `capturePoints()` maps captured piece → material |
| Protocol | `CommandParser`, `StateSerializer`, `Algebraic` | Wire text/JSON ↔ engine calls; AUTH JSON helpers |
| Auth | `AuthController`, `UserService`, `UserRepository`, `PasswordHasher`, `Elo` | AUTH wire → service → SQLite; bcrypt hashes + ELO (server only) |
| Server | `GameSession`, `MatchRoom`, `MatchQueue`, `ConnectionRegistry`, `MatchCoordinator`, `RoomManager`, `WebSocketServer` | Network host; AUTH → PLAY; thin transport dispatches to registry + matchmaking + rooms; `MatchQueue` (ELO±100, 60s); multi-match; auto-tick |
| Graphics | `Animation`, `AnimationCache`, `AnimationLoader`, `BoardLayout`, `PieceVisual`, `IFrameStateSource` | Load/scale sprites, play named state animations, read asset layout — via `Img` only; frame state via `IFrameStateSource` |
| Client | `WebSocketClient`, `SessionBootstrap`, `RemoteStateSource`, `IMatchmaker` | Graphics online path: shell AUTH then Play; I/O thread + inbound queue; no OpenCV |
| View | `Img`, `Renderer` | `Img` wraps OpenCV (`create`, text, blit); `Renderer` composites sprites + optional White/Black history HUD + Play chrome over a wider window |
| App | `App`, `GraphicsApplication`, `main`, `graphics_main`, `server_main` | Wire layers; console, graphics, and server entry points |

### Patterns

- **Strategy**: `IPieceRules` per piece; `RuleEngine` maps kind → strategy (`unordered_map<char, unique_ptr<IPieceRules>>`)
- **DTO**: `MoveResult`, `MoveValidation`, `GameSnapshot`, `ArrivalEvent`, `MotionView`, `RestView`
- **Facade**: `GameEngine` is the single game-logic entry point; `GameSession` wraps it for bus + network
- **Observer**: `EventBus` — game session publishes; subscribers react independently
- **Snapshot**: view never mutates `Board` directly

## Input format (do not change without explicit request)

1. Board rows until `Board:` marker (tokens: `.`, `wK`, `bQ`)
2. `Commands:` — `click X Y`, `jump X Y`, `wait MS`, `print board`
3. Errors to stdout: `ERROR UNKNOWN_TOKEN`, `ERROR ROW_WIDTH_MISMATCH`
4. `jump X Y` lifts the piece at that cell airborne in place for a fixed jump duration (bypasses normal
 travel time since it never changes squares); it lands back down and captures whatever occupies the
 square by then. Rejected if the cell is empty, that color already has a motion in flight, or the
 piece is resting. After landing: travel starts a long rest, jump starts a short rest (`piece_resting`
 until the cooldown ends).

## Code style

- Include guards: `#ifndef BOARD_H` / `#define BOARD_H` / `#endif`
- Classes: PascalCase; methods: camelCase
- Prefer `const` methods and references for read-only params
- File-local helpers as `static` in `.cpp` files
- **Header vs implementation (strict):** `.h` files are headers only — declarations, include guards, `static constexpr` constants, defaulted members. All function/method bodies go in the matching `.cpp`; never define function bodies inline in a header.
- **Prefer `std::unordered_map` over `switch` for extensible key→value tables** (piece kind → rules / points / names, event type → sound cue, etc.). Follow `RuleEngine`'s map pattern. Leave `switch` for small closed enum→string helpers only (`toString(...)`).

## Exception handling (throw up, catch at boundaries)

**Goal:** validate early, throw from inner layers, catch only where errors must be translated or recovered — never log-and-rethrow the same exception at every layer.

```
model / realtime / view(Img)  →  throw only (no try-catch)
         ↓ propagates
rules / engine / input        →  catch & translate to DTO status codes
         ↓ propagates (unexpected)
ScriptRunner / main           →  single catch + log + graceful exit
```

### Model & low-level layers — validation only

Applies to: `model/`, `realtime/`, low-level helpers (`BoardMapper` constructor, `Img`).

- Perform defensive checks; **throw** from `<stdexcept>` when preconditions fail:
  - `std::invalid_argument` — bad arguments, malformed tokens, inconsistent state
  - `std::out_of_range` — grid/cell bounds, invalid coordinates
  - `std::runtime_error` — I/O preconditions (e.g. unreadable stream, missing image)
- **Do not** wrap throws in try-catch here. Let exceptions propagate upward.
- **Do not** log in model/low-level code.

### No redundant catch-and-rethrow

- **Never** add `try { … } catch (const std::exception& e) { std::cerr << …; throw; }` unless local cleanup is required (RAII should handle resources).
- One exception → one log line, at the top boundary only.

### Boundary catchers — translate, don't rethrow

| Layer | Catch when | Return / action |
|-------|------------|-----------------|
| `RuleEngine::validateMove` | `Piece::fromToken` or board access fails | `MoveValidation{ false, "invalid_piece" }` |
| `PieceRules` (`pieceAt`) | token parse fails | `std::nullopt` → `isValidMove` returns `false` |
| `GameEngine::requestMove` / `requestJump` | unexpected runtime error | `MoveResult{ false, "runtime_error" }` |
| `Controller::click` / `jump` | unexpected error during input handling | `ClickResult` / `MoveResult` with `runtime_error` |
| `BoardParser` | — | prefer `BoardParseStatus` enum; throw only for unreadable streams |
| `ScriptRunner::run` | any uncaught `std::exception` | log once to `stderr`, print `ERROR RUNTIME_FAILURE` to stdout, return `false` |
| `main` / `graphics_main` | startup or top-level failure | log once, non-zero exit |

`GameEngine::wait` and `setup` **propagate** exceptions — `ScriptRunner` is the recovery boundary.

### Keep it simple

- No try-catch on operations that cannot realistically fail: `toString()`, basic integer math, trivial getters.
- Catch by `const std::exception&` at boundaries; do not catch `...` unless rethrowing immediately.
- Prefer `#include <stdexcept>` over custom exception types.
